{{Other uses}}
{{wiktionary|orenda}}

'''Orenda''' {{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɔːr|ɛ|n|d|ə}} is an [[Iroquois]] name for a spiritual power inherent in people and their [[Natural environment|environment]].{{sfn|Hewitt|1902}}<ref>{{cite web|title=orenda|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/orenda|website=Merriam-Webster Dictionary|publisher=Merriam-Webster|accessdate=12 April 2015}}</ref> Activities of nature were seen to be a "ceaseless struggle of one orenda against another, uttered and directed by the beings or bodies" in the environment.{{sfn|Hewitt|1902|p=41}} Orenda was deemed a motive force behind miracles, soothsaying, divination, prophecy, blessing, cursing, prayer, worship, and superstitions.{{sfn|Hewitt|1902|p=42}} Orenda is not a collective power and does not have a personification.<ref>{{cite book|title=nature worship|date=2015|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica|url=http://original.search.eb.com/eb/article-38271|accessdate=12 April 2015}}</ref> Nineteenth- and 20th-century scholars compared the concept of orenda to that of [[mana]].<ref>{{cite book|title=mana|date=2015|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica|edition=Web|url=http://original.search.eb.com/eb/article-9050428|accessdate=12 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rose|first1=Herbert Jennings|title=Nvmen and Mana|journal=Harvard Theological Review|date=1951|volume=44|issue=3|pages=109–120|doi=10.1017/s0017816000027760}}</ref>

Anthropologist J. N. B. Hewitt notes intrinsic similarities between the Iroquoian concept of Orenda and that of the [[Sioux]]an wakd or mahopa; the [[Algonquin people|Algonquin]] manitowi, and the pokunt of the [[Shoshone]]. Across the Iroquois tribes, the concept was referred to variously as orenna or karenna by the [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]], [[Cayuga people|Cayuga]], and [[Oneida people|Oneida]]; urente by the [[Tuscarora people|Tuscarora]], and iarenda or orenda by the Huron. A related term, otgon, denoted a specifically "malign, deadly, lethal, or destructive use" of orenda.{{sfn|Hewitt|1902|p=37}} Hewitt notes that orenda was regarded by Iroquoian peoples as distinct from concepts of life, soul, ghost, and mind.{{sfn|Hewitt|1902|p=44}}

For the Iroquois, a shaman was considered to be "one whose orenda is great, powerful", while a hunter's orenda determined whether he was successful in overcoming the orenda of the game, and in conflicts between nations, orenda determined the outcome.{{sfn|Hewitt|1902|p=38}} Orenda was also present in nature: storms were said to possess orenda. A strong connection existed between prayers and songs and orenda: through song, a bird, shaman, or rabbit put forth orenda.{{sfn|Hewitt|1902|p=40-43}}

