{{for2|the [[Romania]]n village of Vinţa|[[Lupşa]]|the Sama-Bajau boat also known as "lepa-lepa"|[[Lepa (ship)]]}} [[File:A Moro vinta outrigger canoe.jpg|thumb|A [[Moro people|Moro]] vinta from the [[Philippines]] (c. 1905)]] [[File:Vinta Boat of the Bajau Laut people.jpg|thumb|A vinta with a plain sail from the [[Bajau]] of [[Borneo]]]] [[File:Vinta boats in Bigiw, Samal Island.jpg|thumb|Colorful non-traditional designs on vintas from [[Samal Island]], [[Philippines]].]] The '''vinta''' (also generically known as ''lepa-lepa'' or ''sakayan'') is a traditional boat from the [[Philippine]] island of [[Mindanao]]. The boats are made by [[Sama-Bajau]] and [[Moro people|Moro]]s living in the [[Sulu Archipelago]],<ref name="jps">{{cite journal |url=http://www.jps.auckland.ac.nz/document/Volume_81_1972/Volume_81%2C_No._2/Wa%2C_vinta%2C_and_trimaran%2C_by_Edwin_Doran_Jnr.%2C_p_144-159/p1?page=0&action=searchresult&target=|title=Wa, Vinta, and Trimaran|first1=Edwin, Jr., [[Texas A&M University]] |last1=Doran |publisher=[[University of Auckland]] |location=[[Auckland]], New Zealand |journal=[[Journal of the Polynesian Society]] |volume=81 |number=2|year=1972 |pages=144{{ndash}}159 |accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref> [[Zamboanga Peninsula|Zamboanga]] peninsula, and southern Mindanao. It has a sail with assorted vertical colors that represents the colorful culture and history of the Muslim community. These boats are used for inter-island transport of people and goods. [[Zamboanga City]] is known for these vessels.
In 1985 the vinta ''[[Sarimanok (vinta)|Sarimanok]]'' was sailed from Bali to Madagascar to replicate ancient seafaring techniques.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gasycool.wordpress.com/2005/11/21/across-the-indian-ocean-aboard-prehistoric-ships/|title=Across the Indian Ocean, aboard prehistoric ships...}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundialsaustralia.com.au/#!navigation-instruments/cqck|title=Navigation Instruments|publisher=Sundials Australia}}</ref>
==Other uses== "Vinta" is also the name of a Moro dance that commemorates the migration of [[Filipino people|Filipinos]] into the archipelago. In the dance, dancers imitating the movements of the vinta (vessel) by balancing perilously on top of poles. PAREF schools in the Philippines have adopted the vinta as their symbol.
